PICANHA! That crispy fat please 🔥
EAT or PASS⁉️ Tag a friend to eat this with
➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖
FOLLOW Me 👉 @meat_with 
➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖

.
That crispy fat! Another reminder of why this is my favorite meat cut. TNX for sharing it with us 📸 @piresigor93 🔥 I go for low and slow till 55C / 130F internal temp. Than fast burning in very high heat (for me it’s 1500F/900C on my Napoleon Sizzle zone) until reaching an internal temperature of 57 C / 134 F (2-3 mins total). Direct fire for the outside fat. 3 minutes rest before cutting.  WOW!
.
.
.
.
.
#picanha #picanheiros #segundafeira #facaselfierro #churrasco

LOBSTER BUTTER BATH 🦞
There is no too much butter on lobster 🦞
EAT or PASS⁉️ Tag a friend to eat this with

.
Crazy lobster butter bath!
thanks for sharing this crazy moment with us  @lasvegasfill (MUST FOLLOW page) continues to serve up the best goods .
.
I'm a big fan of simple Recipe with five ingredients max. If you have a fresh product you should Keep the cook simple. Fresh lobster tails, butter, garlic, salt & pepper (you can add white wine also).
.
.
.
.

SMOKED GOOSE BREAST 🔥
EAT or PASS⁉️ Tag a friend to eat this with
➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖
FOLLOW ➡️ @meat_with
➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖
.
Integrates - Keep it simple - goose breast, Date honey & Wild game all natural seasoning by @myfamilyseasoningsllc 
.
Optional - Asian marinate: soy sauce, Date honey (or teriyaki), sesame oil, ginger, garlic, chili pepper.
.
Prep - Cut the fat gently in a criss-cross shape so that the flavors will penetrate better, the cook will be more accurate both sides  and the appearance will be excellent (After all  we also eat with our eyes). 
.
Low and slow smoked inside my BGE till internal temp 53C/130F. I use my @meatermade ThermoMEATER+. 5 mins rest.
fast burning in very high heat in my sizzle zone (2-3 mins total). 3 minutes rest before cutting. WOW!
Don’t forget cold beer - cheers 🍻
.
.
.
.

Perfect PRIME RIB 🤤
🌿 Seasoning & Recipe by @myfamilyseasoningsllc 
➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖
FOLLOW 👉 @meat_with .
➖➖➖➖➖➖➖➖
.
Credit for my friend 📷 @bbq_bboy (🔝 IG page)
.
Step 1 – Select:
Select the grade and size of your prime rib roast. For best results, we recommend “prime” or “choice” grade of rib roast. Ask your butcher to cut the ribs and tie them on. Do not use a net (seasoning will pull off when your remove net after cooking).
.
Step 2 – Prepare:
One hour prior to cooking, remove the roast from the refrigerator and place in roasting pan. Pour seasoning packaging in small bowl and stir well. One package covers up to 15 pounds of prime rib. For roasts less than five pounds, only use a portion of the seasoning or roast will be too salty! Make sure to top the roast with a little extra seasoning! Place roast fatty side up, ribs down. Cover and set aside for 30 minutes or so. Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
.
Step 3 – Cook:
Place uncovered roasting pan on center rack in oven. Cook approximately 14 to 17 minutes per pound for rare, depending on the size of the roast. remember, a prime rib roast must rest, under a loose covering of aluminum foil, between 15 and 30 minutes after you remove it from the oven. This allows the juices to seep in and the flavors to continue to blend. The roast will gain as much as 20 degrees while resting depending on the cooking temperature, size of the roast, and the length of its rest. Check center of roast for desired doneness using a meat thermometer. End cuts will be more done than center.. We like ours rare. We cook a 12 lb. prime rib for 15 to 17 minutes per/lb. bringing internal temperature to 120 degrees. For our family, this is perfect. Enjoy with au jus, horseradish, and your family’s favorite accompaniments.
.
.
.
